ICYMI: Yesterday, demonstrators gathered in the nation's capital and cities around the world for the third annual @womensmarch. A team from 
@nprviz joined reporters on the ground to capture moments from the rally in D.C. 
Here are some highlights from the D.C. #womensmarch2019:

When it rains in Puerto Rico, it rains hard and it rains fast. And this week — three weeks after Hurricane
 Maria — it has rained a lot. For portions of the island – especially in the mountains and in the valleys – that rain brings a continual trauma of mudslides and flooding. Even in San Juan, highway exits pool with a foot or more of water. But the capital city has fared comparatively well — it's the rural places that are doing much, much worse. And most likely, it won't be the last time: The forecast predicts rain through the weekend. Follow the link in our bio for the full story. (Credit @carolguzy | Carol Guzy
 for NPR)

A big thanks to everyone who shared stories to our #PublicSquare project with @KPCC! In this month's theme, #PSThisIsWhere, we asked you to tell us the story of a place where something happened. It could be something monumental or something personal.

You shared stories from around the globe. We'll feature our favorites with you here on Instagram for the next few days. You can see more on our Picture Show blog and @KPCC's AudioVision.

Here's the history behind the images above (clockwise from top left): @plainviewcrowe - This is where a group of farmers gathered to harvest the crop of a friend who died this summer after he planted this field in April.

@pmarlin - This is where JFK was assassinated in Dallas, Tex.

@kaleykim - This is where you can sit atop the Cliffs of Insanity from "The Princess Bride." @mitzianab - This is where the Big Thompson River hit record flood levels this and split the town of Loveland, Colo., in two.
